[[File:Cupertino_City_Center.jpg|thumb|alt=Cupertino City Center buildings.|For years, Apple ATG offices were in ''[[Cupertino,_California|Cupertino]]'' City Center buildings.]]
The '''Advanced Technology Group''' (ATG) was a corporate research laboratory at [[Apple Inc.|Apple Computer]] from 1986 to 1997.<ref name="Fast Company article June 2018">{{cite web |last1=Diaz |first1=Jesus |title=The legendary Apple research group that shaped our world |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90176202/how-apples-advanced-technology-group-changed-our-world |website=Fast Company |accessdate=11 September 2018 |date=19 June 2018}}</ref> ATG was an evolution of Apple's Education Research Group (ERG) and was started by [[Larry Tesler]] in October 1986 to study long term research into future technologies that were beyond the time frame or organizational scope of any individual product group. Over the next decade, it was led by [[David Nagel]], [[Richard LeFaivre]],<ref name="pcmag lefaivre">{{cite news | url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,1869187,00.asp | title=Rick Lefaivre: Ran Apple's Advanced Technology Group | work=[[PC Magazine]] | date=October 12, 2005 | accessdate=February 27, 2012 | author=Metz, Cade}}</ref> and [[Donald Norman]].<ref name="guardian apple">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/oct/06/why-do-people-hate-apple | title=Why do some people really hate Apple? | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=October 6, 2011 | accessdate=February 27, 2012 | author=Arthur, Charles | quote=[Don] Norman, formerly vice-president of the Advanced Technology Group at Apple [...]}}</ref> It was known as Apple Research Labs during Norman's tenure as VP of the organization. [[Steve Jobs]] closed the group when he returned to Apple in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Davis | first = Jim | title = Apple shutters Advanced Technology Group | publisher = cnet.com | date = October 7, 1997 | url = http://news.cnet.com/2100-1001-203996.html }}</ref>
ATG had research efforts in both hardware and software, with groups focused on such areas as Human-Computer Interaction, Speech Recognition, Educational Technology, Networking, Information Access, Distributed Operating systems, Collaborative Computing, Computer Graphics, and [[Language/action perspective]]. Many of these efforts are described in a special issue of the ACM [[SIGCHI Bulletin]] which provided a retrospective of the ATG work after the lab was shut down. ATG was also home to four Apple Fellows: [[Al Alcorn]], object-oriented software pioneer; [[Alan Kay]]; [[Bill Atkinson]]; and laser printer inventor [[Gary Starkweather]]. Further, ATG funded university research and, starting in 1992, held an annual design competition for teams of students.
Apple's ATG was the birthplace of Color [[QuickDraw]], [[QuickTime]], [[QuickTime VR]], [[QuickDraw 3D]], [[QuickRing]], [[3DMF]] the 3D metafile graphics format, [[ColorSync]], [[HyperCard]], [[Apple events]], [[AppleScript]], Apple's [[PlainTalk]] [[speech recognition]] software, [[Apple Data Detectors]], the V-Twin software for indexing, storing, and searching text documents, [[Macintalk Pro]] [[Speech synthesis|Speech Synthesis]], the [[Newton OS|Newton]] [[Handwriting recognition|handwriting recognizer]],<ref name="arstechnica yaeger">{{cite news | url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/news/2005/06/504.ars | title=In the Loop with Larry Yaeger: part I | work=[[Ars Technica]] | date=June 2005 | accessdate=February 27, 2012 | author=Smykil, Jeff | quote=Also at Apple, in the Advanced Technology Group, [Larry Yaeger] was Technical Lead in the development of the neural network-based handprint recognition system, the world's first genuinely usable handwriting recognition system, showcased in second generation Newton PDAs and Mac OS X's "Inkwell."}}</ref> the component software technology leading to [[OpenDoc]], [[Meta Content Framework|MCF]], [[HotSauce]], [[Squeak]], and the children's programming environment [[Stagecast Creator|Cocoa]] (a trademark Apple later reused for its otherwise unrelated [[Cocoa (API)|Cocoa application frameworks]]).
